segments.text: after the invasion in North Africa.
I thought I was going to be in on that invasion until I found out that the 13th Field Artillery from Fort Bragg, North Carolina.
Now
We fired our guns the first time.
We got new guns and I fired them the first time in Europe.
But, sitting there at Camp Sutton, we were at one end of the big field range up at Fort Bragg.
So the minute I got those guns, they were different from the French GPFs with which this cavalry regiment had been issued for training.
Now these boys that I inherited were cavalrymen, horse cavalrymen.
And the officers were all very fine horsemen and swordsmen.
and could run the courses for shooting pistols and this and that and the other.
And to take a regiment like that and take their damn 16 ounce sabers away from them and give them 16 ton guns of an obsolete French vintage and in order to shoot those French guns
you had to build a storm cellar, dig a recoil pit as deep as a storm cellar in Kansas before you shoot them.
And now to expect trained horse cavalrymen, horsemen over a long period of time, to come in and be
good artilleryman, like that.
Well, of course, it can't be done.
Now, when they, in the, in the... National Guard?
Yes, in the National Guard, there's a lot that they can learn at home.
And what they learn at home,
is really just a school teaching job with exercises on the weekend to get some degree of practicality into it.
Just a laboratory exercise, see.
Now, right today, the average National Guard unit could go on the range up here, now assuming that they have the same equipment
and most of them do.
If they have the same identical equipment and the same identical, when I say equipment I mean range finders.
They can go up there and they can shoot those guns just as good as those guys that have been sitting around for several months waiting for it to become seasonable.
and also you've got to be a good guardsman.
You've got to keep up on your reading, your techniques.
So, and those people, and they do, they can go there.
So, they were well prepared.
give them the same.
Now they may be a little slower doing it than the guys that have done that and grabbed the round of ammunition where it's laying every time he's been on the field and slam it in the reach of the gun.
Some of the guns are still sitting where they were before they were last shot.
At least they were when I was at the school.
So when it comes to the intelligence of the techniques of doing a thing, the guardsmen know it just as well as the regulars.
Sometimes a damn sight better.
I have one last question for you.
And that is, when and why did you retire from the Wisconsin National Guard?
for the simple reason that I had reached the age of sixty.
So, I thought it was a good time to quit.
That's when I first became eligible.
I never thought a National Guardsman would ever get any retired pay.
That's a post-war thing, but
When I was sixty I was on the job and joined it.
So, I would have stayed another year even though I didn't have to or had reached the, it was not, I could have gone to age sixty-four.
But you thought it was a good time for you to retire then?

Well now look, a good friend of mine named, a good friend of mine that was colonel of the other, one of the other regiments in the original 32nd Division, he had been detached from the 32nd Division with
not only himself but the whole regiment off to a place over here.
Now I did have a choice.
When they triangularized the division, the man who supervised the triangularization was a general
I know the name until I have to say it.
But anyway, he stayed on.
Clemens, Clemens, Clemens.
Brigadier General Clemens was at 61, was according to the division command, according to Herman the German.
Kruger.
Kruger.
according to Krueger, he couldn't go overseas.
So, he says now the major general was about a $75,000 a year lawyer, and Milwaukee in those days was pretty close to the top.
You had to have
a terrific set of clients.
But you could have continued if you wanted to, but you just made up your mind that you were not interested in it.
Well, if I had stayed on another year, this guy's name was Bridester, Fritz Bridester.
Fritz Bridester was a graduate of West Point.
He was captain of the football team.
He was one of the great athletes.
You can go up there today and look at their trophies at West Point.
In the period that Prince Bridgestone was there, he was the great man on the field and in soldiering and everything.
He was a big fella.
He went and after West Point he stayed in the Army a couple or three years and married one of the very wealthy families of Milwaukee.
And his wife and her family had barrels of money and they provided the yeast.
That was one of the things they provided for all the beer that was made in Milwaukee.
Well, that's a pretty good monopoly.
Yeah, that sure is.
And that was just one thing they provided.
But he could have had to retire?
He was forced into retirement in Wisconsin?
Well, after he marries this gal, instead of doing like a lot of guys, saying, well,
And he says, I owe the government something.
So he joined the National Guard and he too came in as a captain.
With the West Point diploma he was certainly more qualified than I was.

felt an obligation for his education, although his family was pretty well fixed, too.
And so he came in, and Fritz was always ahead of me, actually, on the list.
But in the matter of warfare, Fritz wound up in a staff job
under, out in the, out in the Orient.
He wound up on a staff job under the, Denninger Joe.
Stillwell.
Yeah, one of the sorriest damn generals that ever pinned on a star.
But nevertheless, a man that captured the imagination.

Well that's maybe more than you'd have time to listen to.
Stilwell was a good old regular army garrison type soldier.
He found himself in a situation where he didn't know what to do, so he decided to just pack up his
toothbrush and shaving kit, if any, and get out and walk across Burma.
Well, a real general would have sent a plane in here, or they'd have gone to the Chiang Kai-shek or whatever his name was, that Chinaman
He said, I'm a general.
I got other things to do.
Now get me out of here damn quick.
Now that's what a general would do.
But this good old honest infantryman had to do the honest thing.
I'll walk out with my people.
See?
That's like God damn grandstand.
But it
Sure did pay off as far as publicity is concerned.
And the documents.
People writing the history of the campaign can't avoid the fact that Vinegar Joe, he was well known, named.
You give me an army officer's nickname and I damn near got his record.
